Introduction to Data Analytics with Python¶

Packages¶

pandas¶

  • a python library for data wrangling, analytics, and manipulation.

bs4¶

  • (Beautiful Soup) a python library for extracting data from webpages.

numpy¶

  • a python library for performing high-level math function (arrays, matrices)

matplotlib¶

  • a python library for visualizing data

Data Scraping¶

In [4]:
# extract data from HTML table
cape_table = soup.find('tbody')

# create arrays to store each variable
instructor, course, term, enroll, evals_made, rcmnd_class, rcmnd_instr, study_hrs, avg_grd_exp, avg_grd_rec = [], [], [], [], [], [], [], [], [], []

# loop through each row in the table and extract data
for row in cape_table.findAll('tr'):
    
    cells = row.findAll('td')

    # This catches when the name cells stops having a link
    #  and ends, skipping the last (summary rows)
    
    try:
        instructor.append(cells[0].find(text=True))
        course.append(cells[1].find('a').text)
        term.append(cells[2].find(text=True))
        enroll.append(cells[3].find(text=True))
        evals_made.append(cells[4].find('span').text)
        rcmnd_class.append(cells[5].find('span').text)
        rcmnd_instr.append(cells[6].find('span').text)
        study_hrs.append(cells[7].find('span').text)
        avg_grd_exp.append(cells[8].find('span').text)
        avg_grd_rec.append(cells[9].find('span').text)
    except:
        break

Dataframes¶

The main functionalities in pandas is to organize and analyze data in dataframes, which are similar to spreadsheets.

They are very useful for altering or manipulating a large volume of data with a few simple functions.

Pandas and python is also convenient in that it can automate routine tasks. (Note: there's even a book called Automate the Boring Stuff with Python)

In [5]:
# add data to a pandas dataframe
cape_df = pd.DataFrame(data={'Instructor': instructor, 'Course': course, 
                             'Term': term, 'Enroll': enroll, 
                             'Evaluations': evals_made, 'Recommend Class (%)': rcmnd_class,

                             'Study Hours': study_hrs,
                             'Average Grade Expected': avg_grd_exp, 
                             'Average Grade Received': avg_grd_rec})

Data Cleaning¶

One of the most necessary skills in data analytics needs is the ability to clean data.

After importing data into data frames, the data is normally very "messy."

Ex. missing data/NA values, incorrect/unconverted data types, unstandardized data, misordered data, unusable data etc.

Cleaning data often requires addressing most or all of the above issues.

Pandas makes this much easier to deal with.

Dealing with Missing Data¶

  • Often times you will not have a complete dataset
  • It is important that you evaluate your options when it comes to missing data
    • Deleting the values completely
    • Setting the values to 0

In this case we decided to delete the values in order to not skew the data.

In [6]:
# Drop rows with N/A values

cape_df = cape_df[cape_df['Average Grade Received'] != 'N/A']
cape_df = cape_df[cape_df['Average Grade Expected'] != 'N/A']

Standardizing Data¶

  • Data isn't perfect. So we need to standardize data inputs.
    • incorrect spelling
    • lots of spaces
    • duplicate inputs
    • inconsistent capitalization

Ex: In our dataframe we have:

'COGS 1 - Introduction to Cognitive Sci (A)',
'COGS 1 - Introduction to Cognitive Sci (B)',
'COGS 1   - Introduction to Cognitive Sci  (A)',
'COGS 1 - Introduction to Cognitive Sci  (A)',

When we really just want:

'COGS 1 - Introduction to Cognitive Sci'
In [7]:
# Standardize Course Name (get rid of section)

def stnd_course(course):
  course = str(course)
  course = course.strip()
  temp = course.split('-')
  temp[0] = temp[0].strip()
  temp[1] = temp[1].strip()
  course = temp[0] + ' - ' + temp[1]
  course.strip()
  return course [:-4]

cape_df['Course'] = cape_df['Course'].apply(stnd_course)
cape_df['Course'] = cape_df['Course'].str.strip()
In [8]:
# Standardize the Instructor Name (get rid of whitespaces)
cape_df['Instructor'] = cape_df['Instructor'].str.strip()

Incorrect/Unconverted Data Types¶

Currently every column's data type in our dataframe is an object when we want numerical types because numerical types are easier to perform data analysis on.

Currently the data types we have are:

Instructor                  object
Course                      object
Term                        object
Enroll                      object
Evaluations                 object
Recommend Class (%)         object
Recommend Instructor (%)    object
Study Hours                 object
Average Grade Expected      object
Average Grade Received      object
dtype: object

We want:

Instructor                   object
Course                       object
Term                         object
Year                          int64
Quarter                       int64
Enroll                        int64
Evaluations                   int64
Recommend Class (%)         float64
Recommend Instructor (%)    float64
Study Hours                 float64
Average Grade Expected       object
GPA Expected                float64
Average Grade Received       object
GPA Received                float64
dtype: object
In [9]:
# maps each quarter to a numerical value
quarter_map = {'FA': 1, 'WI': 2, 'SP': 3, 'SU':4, 'S1': 4, 'S2':5}

def getYear(term):
  return int(term[2:])

def getQuarter(term):
  return quarter_map[term[0:2]]

Year = cape_df['Term'].apply(getYear)
Quarter = cape_df['Term'].apply(getQuarter)

cape_df.insert(3, "Year", Year, True)
cape_df.insert(4, "Quarter", Quarter, True)
In [10]:
# Add Average Grade Expected and Average Grade Received in terms in GPA

def to_gpa(grade):
  return float(grade[-5:len(grade)-1])

GPA_Expected = cape_df['Average Grade Expected'].apply(to_gpa)
GPA_Received = cape_df['Average Grade Received'].apply(to_gpa)

cape_df.insert(11, "GPA Expected", GPA_Expected)
cape_df.insert(13, "GPA Received", GPA_Received)
In [11]:
# Convert Recommend Class, Recommend Instructor columns to floats

def to_num(rec):
  return float(rec[:len(rec)-1])

cape_df['Recommend Class (%)'] = cape_df['Recommend Class (%)'].apply(to_num)
cape_df['Recommend Instructor (%)'] = cape_df['Recommend Instructor (%)'].apply(to_num)
In [12]:
# Convert the rest of the columns to numerical values
cape_df[['Enroll', 'Evaluations', 'Study Hours']] = cape_df[['Enroll', 'Evaluations', 'Study Hours']].apply(pd.to_numeric)

Data Visualizations¶

You can create data visualizations using either the pandas package or matplotlib. (Other packages exist, but we will only be going over these)

matplotlib also allows you to create a variety of data visualizations.

panda.DataFrame.plot uses matplotlib's functionality in order to create visualizations directly from your dataframe.

  • line : line plot (default)
  • bar : vertical bar plot
  • barh : horizontal bar plot
  • hist : histogram
  • box : boxplot
  • kde : Kernel Density Estimation plot
  • density : same as kde
  • area : area plot
  • pie : pie plot
  • scatter : scatter plot
  • hexbin : hexbin plot

Notation is slightly different.

Bar Plot¶

courses = ['COGS 1 - Introduction to Cognitive Sci', 
           'COGS 10 - Cognitv Consequence/Technology', 
           'COGS 13 - Fld Methods: Cognition in Wild',
           'COGS 14A - Intro. to Research Methods',

           'COGS 17 - Neurobiology of Cognition', 
           'COGS 18 - Introduction to Python']

# find average hours per course
avg_course_grd = []
for course in courses:
  avg_course_grd.append(cape_df[cape_df['Course'] == course]['Study Hours'].mean())

# create label names -- only include the course number (just makes things cleaner to look at)
labels = []
for i in courses:
  labels.append(i.split(" -")[0])
In [25]:
# plot the bar graph
plt.bar(courses, avg_course_grd)

# styles x-axis, and adds axis labels.

plt.xlabel("Course")
plt.ylabel("Study Hours")
plt.show()
